post_text:
Today the 8th graders met with Jessie and Elliott from the Soldiers of Destiny motor scooter club. They shared their story of riding 125 CC scooters from Florida to Washington state (3,700 miles!!!). They even made a documentary about it called Slow Ride Home.

8th graders, the final Zoom session of the year will be held tomorrow (Wednesday) where the 8th grade reflection video will be shown. 8th grade students were encouraged to submit photos and/or a short video reflecting on their favorite middle school memories for a short video that is being put together. For details, 8th graders can check out the email that was sent to them last week.

We have a very special guest joining our Zoom on Tuesday, May 5th at 11am. It's someone that we have talked about before. His name is Tom Rinaldi and he is a reporter for ESPN. He is the man that put together The Man in the Red Bandana. 7th graders- This is the guy we were going to interview in the fall but it didn't work out. 8th graders- We have watched this in class and Tom is a master researcher.

Our focus will be on primary source research, with his work on the ESPN piece being the case study.

Please watch the video linked below before we meet with him on Tuesday. This Zoom is open to NHMS 7th and 8th graders.

https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/11505494/lang/en

post_text:
Parents and Students:

This closure has been tough on parents, students, teachers, and staff. Let’s find a positive way to support each other! The week of May 4th-May 8th is teacher appreciation week. We are not going to be able to see our teachers to thank them for all they do for us due to the physical school being closed. Let’s create a shower of appreciation to our teachers thanking them for all they do through emails, notes, videos, pictures, or other ways. You can add comments on Facebook or send responses to Mr. Manson m_manson@new-hampton.k12.ia.us and I will post on Facebook for everyone to see our community support of our teachers!

#NHTribe
text:

We are not going to be able to see our teachers to thank them for all they do for us due to the physical school being closed. Let’s create a shower of appreciation to our teachers thanking them for all they do through emails, notes, videos, pictures, or other ways. post_text:
Update on the meal program:

Beginning Monday March 30th we will be changing our Grab & Go meal distribution days to 3 days per week at all of our delivery/pickup sites. We will distribute on Mondays, Wednesdays, & Fridays. Each person will receive 2 days worth of breakfast & 2 days worth of lunch. Times are still the same from 11:30-12:30. These free meals are available to any person age 1-18. Please contact any of the school offices to sign up if you are not currently participating and would like to. Delivery/pickup sites are the Elementary Playground, Mikkleson Park, Alta Vista City Hall Parking Lot, Immaculate Conception in North Washington, Jerico Joe's in Jerico, and Ionia city park.
*Meals may contain allergens*

shared_text:
New Hampton Community Schools
March 3 at 5:47 PM ·

I see a lot of posts related to our notification of the verbal threat incident at the high school this morning. We elected to use social media as we felt that was the quickest way to get the word out on the incident to our parents and community members. Some posts that have been shared since are simply inaccurate information and some posts appear to only have the purpose of trying to incite others. If someone makes a threat and the police are notified, it’s highly unlikely that the student will simply be “sent home”. If this was your child, you would want the district to preserve and protect his or her privacy as we do for every student. As soon as the district learned of the threat, we responded appropriately and fully addressed it with the assistance of law enforcement to make sure it is properly handled and all students and staff remain safe.

We elected to use social media as we felt that was the quickest way to get the word out on the incident to our parents and community members. Some posts that have been shared since are simply inaccurate information and some posts appear to only have the purpose of trying to incite others. If someone makes a threat and the police are notified, it’s highly unlikely that the student will simply be “sent home”. If this was your child, you would want the district to preserve and protect his or her privacy as we do for every student. As soon as the district learned of the threat, we responded appropriately and fully addressed it with the assistance of law enforcement to make sure it is properly handled and all students and staff remain safe.

February 3-7 is National Counseling Week and we want to bring awareness to all of the things done by our counselors. We will be having some fun dress up days!

Monday-School Counselors help us prepare for our future- (Wear a shirt representing a career or college)

Tuesday- School Counselors show and teach us kindness and be positive! (Wear a positive message shirt)

Wednesday- School Counselors listen and help us when we are feeling blue- (Wear blue jeans)

Thursday- School Counselors like to hear about and celebrate our accomplishments on our bright days! (Wear bright colors)

Friday- School Counselors are an important part of our TRIBE- (Wear TRIBE/Chickasaw Shirts)
